:"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-11217/canvas/1/5c5d32e1-5ba8-4077-9172-9b851dd63af5","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T19:09:44.141Z","creator":"lucia","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>The close-up of the tea kettle makes it resemble a smoking gun. This scene is the clearest and strongest example of the “tea kettle as weapon and locus of tension” motif. <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW198093990 BCX2\" href=\"https://digbmc.github.io/pt-annotated/items/phan-15620.html\"><u>Another example</u></a> can be seen near the end of the film during the dramatic second poisoning. Pouring and drinking tea comes to represent characters’ power over others.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-11217/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:384.1350210970464,247.6793248945148,994.4303797468356,731.1392405063289"}}}]}]}]}